==Associated conditions (potential complications)==
* [[Left ventricular hypertrophy]] and left [[ventricular remodeling]]<ref name = "Messerli 1996" />
* Diminished [[coronary flow reserve]] and silent [[myocardial ischemia]] <ref name = "Messerli 1996" />
* [[Coronary heart disease]] and accelerated [[atherosclerosis]]<ref name = "Messerli 1996" />
* [[Congestive heart failure]], including Heart Failure With Normal Left Ventricular Ejection Fraction (HFNEF),<ref name = "Maeder 2009">{{cite journal | authorformat = vanc | last1 = Maeder | first1 = M. T. | last2 = Kaye | first2 = D. M. | title = Heart failure with normal left ventricular ejection fraction | journal = [[Journal of the American College of Cardiology]] | volume = 53 | issue = 11 | pages = 905–918 | year = 2009 | month = March | pmid = 19281919 | doi = 10.1016/j.jacc.2008.12.007 }}</ref> often termed [[diastolic heart failure]]<ref name = "Messerli 1996" />
* [[Atrial fibrillation]], other [[cardiac arrhythmias]] and [[sudden cardiac death]]<ref name = "Messerli 1996" />

==Differential diagnosis==
Other conditions can share features with hypertensive heart disease and need to be considered in the differential diagnosis. For example:
*Coronary artery disease or [[ischemic heart disease]] due to atherosclerosis
*[[Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy]]
*Left ventricular hypertrophy in athletes
*Congestive heart failure or heart failure with normal ejection fraction due to other causes
*Atrial fibrillation or other disorders of cardiac rhythm due to other causes
*[[Sleep apnea]]

==Treatment==
The medical care of patients with hypertensive heart disease falls under 2 categories—<ref name=Medscape>{{cite web|last=Riaz|first=Kamran|title=Hypertensive Heart Disease|url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/162449-overview|publisher=Medscape Reference|accessdate=17 February 2013}}</ref> 
* Treatment of the elevated BP 
* Prevention and treatment of hypertensive heart disease.

===Prevention===
Because there are no symptoms with high blood pressure, people can have the condition without knowing it. Diagnosing high blood pressure early can help prevent heart disease, stroke, eye problems, and chronic kidney disease.<ref name=Medline>{{cite web|title=Hypertensive heart disease|url=http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/000163.htm|publisher=Medline Plus|accessdate=17 February 2013}}</ref> 

The risk of cardiovascular disease and death can be reduced by lifestyle modifications, including dietary advice, promotion of weight loss and regular aerobic exercise, moderation of alcohol intake and cessation of smoking.<ref name=JNC7 /> Drug treatment may also be needed to control the hypertension and reduce the risk of cardiovascular disease,<ref name=JNC7 /> manage the heart failure,<ref>{{cite journal | authorformat = vanc | last1 = Hunt | first1 = Sharon Ann | last2 = Abraham | first3 = William T. | last3 = Chin | first3 = Marshall H. | first4 = Arthur M. | last4 = Feldman | first5 = Gary S. | last5 = Francis | first6 = Theodore G. | last6 = Ganiats | first7 = Mariell | last7 = Jessup | first8 = Marvin A. | last8 = Konstam | first9 = Donna M. | last9 = Mancini | first10 = Keith | last10 = Michl | first11 = John A. | last11 = Oates | first12 = Peter S. | last12 = Rahko | first13 = Marc A. | last13 = Silver | first14 = Lynne Warner | last14 = Stevenson | first15 = Clyde W. | last15 = Yancy | title = 2009 focused update incorporated into the ACC/AHA 2005 Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Heart Failure in Adults: a report of the American College of Cardiology Foundation/American Heart Association Task Force on Practice Guidelines: developed in collaboration with the International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation | journal = [[Circulation (journal)|Circulation]] | volume = 119 | issue = 14 | pages = e391–479 | year = 2009 | month = April | pmid = 19324966 | doi = 10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.109.192065 }}</ref> or control cardiac arrhythmias.<ref>{{cite journal | authorformat = vanc | last1 = Fuster | first1 = Valentin | last2 = Rydén | first2 = Lars E. | last3 = Cannom | first3 = Davis S. | first4 = Harry J. | last4 = Crijns | first5 = Anne B. | last5 = Curtis | first6 = Kenneth A. | last6 = Ellenbogen | first7 = Jonathan L. | last7= Halperin | first8 = G. Neal | last8 = Kay | first9 = Jean-Yves | last9 = Le Huezey | first10 = James E. | last10 = Lowe | first11 = S. Bertil | last11 = Olsson | first12 = Eric N. | last12 = Prystowsky | first13 = Juan Luis | last13 = Tamargo | first14 = L. Samuel | last14 = Wann | title=2011 ACCF/AHA/HRS focused updates incorporated into the ACC/AHA/ESC 2006 Guidelines for the management of patients with atrial fibrillation: a report of the American College of Cardiology Foundation/American Heart Association Task Force on Practice Guidelines developed in partnership with the European Society of Cardiology and in collaboration with the European Heart Rhythm Association and the Heart Rhythm Society | journal=[[Journal of the American College of Cardiology]] | volume=57 | issue=11 | pages=e101–98 | year=2011 | month=March | pmid=21392637 |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2010.09.013 }}</ref> Patients with hypertensive heart disease should avoid taking over the counter [[non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs]] (NSAIDs), or cough suppressants, and decongestants containing [[sympathomimetics]], unless otherwise advised by their physician as these can exacerbate hypertension and heart failure.<ref>{{cite journal | authorformat = vanc | last1 = White | first1 = William B. | title = Cardiovascular risk, hypertension, and NSAIDs | journal = [[Current Rheumatology Reports]] | volume = 9 | issue = 1 |pages = 36–43 | year = 2007 | month = April | pmid = 17437665 |doi=10.1007/s11926-007-0020-3 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |authorformat = vanc | last1 = Ackman | first1 = M. L. | last2 = Campbell | first2 = J. B. | last3 = Buzak | first3 = K. A. | last4 = Tsuyuki | first4 = R. T. | last5 = Montague | first5 = T. J. | last6 = Teo | first6 = K. K. | title = Use of nonprescription medications by patients with congestive heart failure | journal = [[Annals of Pharmacotherapy]] | volume = 33 | issue = 6 | pages = 674–679 | year = 1999 | month = June | pmid = 10410177 | doi = 10.1345/aph.18283 }}</ref>

===Blood Pressure Goals===
According to JNC 7, BP goals should be as follows :<ref name=JNC7 /> 
* Less than 140/90mm Hg in patients with uncomplicated hypertension
* Less than 130/85mm Hg in patients with diabetes and those with renal disease with less than 1g/24-hour proteinuria
* Less than 125/75mm Hg in patients with renal disease and more than 1 g/24-hour proteinuria

