Hypertension or high blood pressure affects at least 1 billion people worldwide.<ref name="pmid15652604">{{cite journal | authorformat = vanc | last1 = Kearney | first1 = Patricia M. | last2 = Whelton | first2 = Megan | last3 = Reynolds | first3 = Kristi | last4 = Muntner | first4 = Paul | last5 = Whelton | first5 = Paul K. | last6 = He | first6 = Jiang | title = Global burden of hypertension: analysis of worldwide data | journal = [[The Lancet]] | volume = 365 | issue = 9455 | pages = 217–223 | year = 2005 | pmid = 15652604 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(05)17741-1 }}</ref> Hypertensive heart disease is only one of several diseases attributable to high [[blood pressure]]. Other diseases caused by high blood pressure include [[ischemic heart disease]], [[stroke]], [[peripheral arterial disease]], [[aneurysms]] and [[kidney disease]]. Hypertension increases the risk of heart failure by two or three-fold <ref name=JNC7 /> and probably accounts for about 25% of all cases of heart failure.<ref>{{cite journal | authorformat = vanc | last1 = Kannel | first1 = W. B. | last2 = Cobb | first2 = J. |title = Left ventricular hypertrophy and mortality—results from the Framingham Study | journal =[[Cardiology (journal)|Cardiology]] | volume = 81 | issue = 4–5 | pages = 291–298 | year = 1992 | pmid = 1301257 | doi = 10.1159/000175819 }}</ref> In addition, hypertension precedes heart failure in 90% of cases,<ref name=JNC7 /> and the majority of heart failure in the elderly may be attributable to hypertension.<ref>{{cite journal | authorformat = vanc | last1 = Yamasaki | first1 = Naohito | last2 = Kitaoka | first2 = Hiroaki | last3 = Matsumura | first3 = Yoshihisa | last4 = Furuno | first4 = Takashi | last5 = Nishinaga | first5 = Masanori | last6 = Doi | first6 = Yoshinori | title = Heart failure in the elderly | journal = [[Internal Medicine (journal)|Internal Medicine]] | volume = 42 | issue = 5 | pages = 383–388 | year = 2003 | month = May | pmid = 12793706 | doi = 10.2169/internalmedicine.42.383 }}</ref> Hypertensive heart disease was estimated to be responsible for 1.0 million deaths worldwide in 2004 (or approximately 1.7% of all deaths globally), and was ranked 13th in the leading global causes of death for all ages.<ref>{{cite book |author=World Health Organization |title=The Global Burden of Disease: 2004 Update |publisher=World Health Organization |location=Geneva |year=2008 |isbn=92-4-156371-0 }}</ref> A world map shows the estimated disability-adjusted life years per 100,000 inhabitants lost due to hypertensive heart disease in 2004.<ref name="Ref_2009"/>

=== Gender differences in hypertensive heart disease===
There are more women than men with hypertension,<ref>{{cite journal | authorformat = vanc | first1 = Kathryn | last1 = Anastos | first2 = Pamela | last2 = Charney | first3 = Rita A. | last3 = Charon | first4 = Ellen | last4 = Cohen | first5 = Clara Y. | last5 = Jones | first6 = Carola | last6 = Marte | first7 = Deborah M. | last7 = Swiderski | first8 = Mary E. | last8 = Wheat | first9 = Sarah | last9 = Williams | title = Hypertension in women: what is really known? The Women's Caucus, Working Group on Women's Health of the Society of General Internal Medicine | journal = [[Annals of Internal Medicine]] | volume = 115 | issue = 4 | pages = 287–293 | year = 1991 | month = August | pmid = 1854113 | url = http://annals.org/article.aspx?articleid=704912 }}</ref> and, although men develop hypertension earlier in life,<ref name="Rabi">{{cite journal | authorformat = vanc | last1 = Rabi | first1 = Doreen M. | last2 = Khan | first2 = Nadia | last3 = Vallée | first3 = Michel | last4 = Hladunewich | first4 = Michelle A. | last5 = Tobe | first5 = Sheldon W. | last6 = Pilote | first6 = Louise | title = Reporting on sex-based analysis in clinical trials of angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor and angiotensin receptor blocker efficacy | journal = [[Canadian Journal of Cardiology]] | volume = 24 | issue = 6 | pages = 491–496 | year = 2008 | month = June | pmid = 18548147 | pmc = 2643194 | doi = 10.1016/S0828-282X(08)70624-X }}</ref> hypertension in women is less well controlled.<ref>{{cite journal | authorformat = vanc | last1 = Lloyd-Jones | first1 = Donald M. | last2 = Evans | first2 = Jane C. | last3 = Levy | first3 = Daniel | title = Hypertension in adults across the age spectrum: current outcomes and control in the community | journal = [[JAMA (journal)|JAMA]] | volume = 294 | issue = 4 | pages = 466–472 | year = 2005 | month = July | pmid = 16046653 | doi = 10.1001/jama.294.4.466 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | authorformat = vanc | first1 = Sylvia | last1 = Wassertheil-Smoller | first2 = Garnet | last2 = Anderson | first3 = Bruce M. | last3 = Psaty | first4 = Henry R. | last4 = Black | first5 = JoAnn | last5 = Manson | first6 = Nathan | last6 = Wong | first7 = Jon | last7 = Francis | first8 = Richard | last8 = Grimm | first9 = Theodore | last9 = Kotchen | first10 = Robert | last10 = Langer | first11 = Norman | last11 = Lasser | title = Hypertension and its treatment in postmenopausal women: baseline data from the Women's Health Initiative | journal = [[Hypertension (journal)|Hypertension]] | volume = 36 | issue = 5 | pages = 780–789 | year = 2000 | month = November | pmid = 11082143 | url = http://hyper.ahajournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=11082143 | doi = 10.1161/01.HYP.36.5.780 }}</ref> The consequences of high blood pressure in women are a major public health problem and hypertension is a more important contributory factor in heart attacks in women than men.<ref name="Rabi" /> Until recently women have been under-represented in clinical trials in hypertension and heart failure. Nevertheless, there is some evidence that the effectiveness of antihypertensive drugs differs between men and women<ref name="Rabi" /> and that treatment for heart failure may be less effective in women.<ref name= "Bui 2011">{{cite journal | authorformat = vanc | first1 = Anh L. | last1 = Bui | first2 = Tamara B. | last2 = Horwich | first3 = Gregg C. | last3 = Fonarow | title = Epidemiology and risk profile of heart failure | journal = [[Nature Reviews Cardiology]] | volume = 8 | issue = 1 | pages = 30–41 | year = 2011 | month = January | pmid = 21060326 | pmc = 3033496 | doi = 10.1038/nrcardio.2010.165 }}</ref>

=== Ethnic disparities in hypertensive heart disease===
Studies in the USA indicate that a disproportionate number of African Americans have hypertension compared with non-Hispanic whites and Mexican Americans, and that they suffer a greater burden of hypertensive heart disease.<ref name = Ferdinand>{{cite journal | authorformat = vanc | first1 = Keith C. | last1 = Ferdinand | first2 = Elijah | last2 = Sounders  | title = Hypertension-related morbidity and mortality in African Americans—why we need to do better | journal = [[Journal of Clinical Hypertension]] (Greenwich) | volume = 8 | issue = 1 Suppl 1 | pages = 21–30 | year = 2006 | month = January | pmid = 16415637 | doi = 10.1111/j.1524-6175.2006.05295.x }}</ref> Heart failure is more common in people of African American ethnicity, mortality from heart failure is also consistently higher than in white patients, and it develops at an earlier age.<ref name= "Bui 2011" /><ref>{{cite journal |authorformat = vanc | first1 = Laura R. | last1 = Loehr | first2 = Wayne D. | last2 = Rosamond | first3 = Patricia P. | last3 = Chang | first4 = Aaron R. | last4 = Folsom | first5 = Lloyd E. | last5 = Chambless | title = Heart failure incidence and survival (from the Atherosclerosis Risk in Communities study) | journal = [[American Journal of Cardiology]] | volume = 101 | issue = 7 | pages = 1016–1022 | year = 2008 | month = April | pmid = 18359324 | doi = 10.1016/j.amjcard.2007.11.061 }}</ref>  Worryingly, recent data suggests that rates of hypertension are increasing more rapidly in African Americans than other ethnic groups.<ref>{{cite journal | authorformat = vanc | first1 = Donald | last1 = Lloyd-Jones | first2 = Robert | last2 = Adams | first3 = Mercedes | last3 = Carnethon | first4 = Giovanni | last4 = De Simone | first5 = T. Bruce | last5 = Ferguson | first6 = Katherine | last6 = Flegal | first7 = Earl | last7 = Ford | first8 = Karen | last8 = Furie | first9 = Alan | last9 = Go | first10 = Kurt | last10 = Greenlund | first11 = Nancy | last11 = Haase | first12 = Susan | last12 = Hailpern | first13 = Michael | last13 = Ho | first14 = Virginia | last14 = Howard | first15 = Brett | last15 = Kissela | first16 = Steven | last16 = Kittner | first17 = Daniel | last17 = Lackland | first18 = Lynda | last18 = Lisabeth | first19 = Ariane | last19 = Marelli | first20 = Mary | last20 = McDermott | first21 = James | last21 = Meigs | first22 = Dariush | last22 = Mozaffarian | first23 = Graham | last23 = Nichol | first24 = Christopher | last24 = O'Donnell | first25 = Veronique | last25 = Roger | first26 = Wayne | last26 = Rosamond | first27 = Ralph | last27 = Sacco | first28 = Paul | last28 = Sorlie | first29 = Randall | last29 = Stafford | first30 = Julia | last30 = Steinberger | first31 = Thomas | last31 = Thom | first32 = Sylvia | last32 = Wasserthiel-Smoller | first33 = Nathan | last33 = Wong | first34 = Judith | last34 = Wylie-Rosett | first35 = Yuling | last35 = Hong | title = Heart disease and stroke statistics—2009 update: a report from the American Heart Association Statistics Committee and Stroke Statistics Subcommittee | journal = [[Circulation (journal)|Circulation]] | volume = 119 | issue = 3 | pages = e21–181 | year = 2009 | month = January | pmid = 19075105 | doi = 10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.108.191261 | url = http://circ.ahajournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=19075105 }}</ref> The excess of high blood pressure and its consequences in African Americans is likely to contribute to their shorter life expectancy compared with white Americans.<ref name = Ferdinand />

